05336nam a22007215i 9780691226514DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912265147 a10.1515/97806912265142doi  a(DE-B1597)583280  a(OCoLC)1259320219  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823.8093532231 aSchaffer, Talia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommunities of Care :bThe Social Ethics of Victorian Fiction /cTalia Schaffer. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Care Communities Today -- tChapter 1 Ethics of Care and the Care Community -- tchapter 2 Austen, Dickens, and Brontë: Bodies before the Normate -- tchapter 3 Global Migrant Care and Emotional Labor in Villette -- tchapter 4 Beyond Sympathy: The State of Care in Daniel Deronda -- tchapter 5 Care Meets the Silent Treatment in The Wings of the Dove -- tchapter 6 Composite Fiction and the Care Community in The Heir of Redclyffe -- tEpilogue: Critical Care -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat we can learn about caregiving and community from the Victorian novelIn Communities of Care, Talia Schaffer explores Victorian fictional representations of care communities, small voluntary groups that coalesce around someone in need. Drawing lessons from Victorian sociality, Schaffer proposes a theory of communal care and a mode of critical reading centered on an ethics of care.In the Victorian era, medical science offered little hope for cure of illness or disability, and chronic invalidism and lengthy convalescences were common. Small communities might gather around afflicted individuals to minister to their needs and palliate their suffering. Communities of Care examines these groups in the novels of Jane Austen, Charlotte Brontë, Charles Dickens, George Eliot, Henry James, and Charlotte Yonge, and studies the relationships that they exemplify. How do carers become part of the community? How do they negotiate status? How do caring emotions develop? And what does it mean to think of care as an activity rather than a feeling? Contrasting the Victorian emphasis on community and social structure with modern individualism and interiority, Schaffer's sympathetic readings draw us closer to the worldview from which these novels emerged. Schaffer also considers the ways in which these models of carework could inform and improve practice in criticism, in teaching, and in our daily lives.Through the lens of care, Schaffer discovers a vital form of communal relationship in the Victorian novel. Communities of Care also demonstrates that literary criticism done well is the best care that scholars can give to texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCare of the sick in literature. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691226514zCo